-- bb-lesson-t-embedded: Basic Embedded Systems
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Real-Time Embedded Control", "content": "The Ball and Beam system operates as a real-time embedded control system in which a microcontroller continuously reads the position of the ball, computes a corrective action, and commands a motor to adjust the beam angle.\n\nUnlike traditional desktop programs that run once and terminate, embedded systems execute in a continuous loop. In the Arduino environment, every program is organized around two core functions:\n\n- **`setup()`** - Runs once at startup, initializes hardware components\n- **`loop()`** - Runs repeatedly, forms the core control cycle\n\nWithin the loop, the microcontroller repeatedly performs three essential steps:\n1. Measure the ball''s position\n2. Calculate the control output\n3. Update the actuator"}, {"title": "Hardware Interfacing", "content": "To interface with hardware, pins must be properly configured as inputs or outputs using `pinMode()`.\n\n**Sensor Reading:**\nSensors such as potentiometers or distance sensors are typically read using `analogRead()`, which converts a voltage signal into a digital value using the microcontroller''s internal analog-to-digital converter.\n\n**Actuator Control:**\nActuators such as motors are controlled using digital signals or Pulse Width Modulation (PWM). PWM allows the microcontroller to simulate an analog output by rapidly switching a pin on and off with a controllable duty cycle.\n\n```cpp\nvoid setup() {\n    pinMode(SENSOR_PIN, INPUT);\n    pinMode(MOTOR_PIN, OUTPUT);\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n    int position = analogRead(SENSOR_PIN);\n    int output = calculateControl(position);\n    analogWrite(MOTOR_PIN, output);\n}\n```"}, {"title": "Timing in Control Systems", "content": "Timing is a critical component of any control system. The control loop must run at consistent intervals to ensure stable and predictable behavior.\n\n**Non-Blocking Timing:**\nInstead of using blocking delays that pause execution, embedded systems should rely on non-blocking timing methods such as `millis()` to maintain a steady loop frequency.\n\n```cpp\nunsigned long previousTime = 0;\nconst unsigned long LOOP_INTERVAL = 10;  // 10ms\n\nvoid loop() {\n    unsigned long currentTime = millis();\n    \n    if (currentTime - previousTime >= LOOP_INTERVAL) {\n        previousTime = currentTime;\n        \n        // Control loop runs every 10ms\n        readSensor();\n        computeControl();\n        updateActuator();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis ensures the system remains responsive and capable of updating sensor readings and motor commands at a fixed rate. Consistent timing becomes especially important when implementing feedback control algorithms such as PID."}, {"title": "Libraries and Serial Debugging", "content": "**Libraries:**\nLibraries are commonly used to simplify interaction with hardware components like ultrasonic sensors, servo motors, or communication modules. While these libraries abstract lower-level details, it is important to understand that they are:\n- Configuring timers\n- Managing communication protocols (I2C, SPI)\n- Handling signal timing\n\nA strong embedded systems engineer understands not only how to call library functions, but also what those functions are doing internally.\n\n**Serial Communication:**\nSerial communication is an essential debugging tool in embedded development. By printing sensor values, control signals, and tuning parameters to the Serial Monitor, you can observe system behavior in real time and diagnose issues systematically.\n\n```cpp\nvoid setup() {\n    Serial.begin(115200);\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n    int position = readSensor();\n    int output = calculateControl(position);\n    \n    Serial.print(\"Position: \");\n    Serial.print(position);\n    Serial.print(\" Output: \");\n    Serial.println(output);\n}\n```\n\nThis mirrors professional engineering practice, where logging and measurement are critical for validating system performance."}], "key_points": ["setup() runs once, loop() runs continuously", "Use non-blocking timing with millis()", "PWM controls motor speed", "Serial debugging is essential for tuning"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'bb-lesson-t-embedded';

-- bb-lesson-t-circuits: Circuit Creation and Breadboarding
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Understanding Circuit Layout", "content": "Before the Ball and Beam system can be controlled in software, the hardware must be assembled correctly and safely. The goal is not simply to \"wire it up,\" but to understand:\n- Power flow\n- Signal flow\n- Grounding strategy\n- Component interaction"}, {"title": "Power Distribution", "content": "Every embedded circuit begins with power distribution. The microcontroller typically operates at 5V or 3.3V, and all sensors and logic components must share a common ground reference.\n\nOn a breadboard:\n- Connect the microcontroller''s GND to the ground rail\n- Distribute VCC to the positive rail\n- Connect all sensor and driver modules to these same rails\n\n**Critical:** A shared ground is essential. Without it, voltage readings become meaningless and control signals behave unpredictably."}, {"title": "Core Hardware Blocks", "content": "The Ball and Beam system typically consists of three core hardware blocks:\n\n**1. Microcontroller**\n- Central processing unit\n- Runs the control algorithm\n- Interfaces with sensors and actuators\n\n**2. Position Sensor**\n- Potentiometer, ultrasonic sensor, or IR distance sensor\n- Provides voltage or digital signal representing ball location\n- Connected to analog or digital input pin\n- Must ensure voltage levels are within allowable range (5V tolerance or level shifting)\n\n**3. Motor Driver**\n- Cannot drive motor directly from microcontroller pin (insufficient current)\n- H-bridge for DC motors\n- PWM control for servos\n- Acts as power interface between logic and motor"}, {"title": "Wiring Best Practices", "content": "When placing components on a breadboard, follow structured wiring practices:\n\n- **Power rails organized** - Keep VCC and GND clearly separated\n- **Consistent wire colors** - Red for VCC, black for GND\n- **Short signal wires** - Reduces noise\n- **Avoid crossing wires** - Prevents confusion and shorts\n- **Separate motor wires** - Keep high-current motor wires away from sensitive sensor lines\n\n**Decoupling Capacitors:**\nPlacing small capacitors (e.g., 0.1 uF) across power and ground near sensitive components helps filter voltage spikes and noise caused by motors switching on and off."}, {"title": "Incremental Verification", "content": "Build and validate one subsystem at a time to prevent compounding errors:\n\n**Step 1:** Confirm power rails supply correct voltage using a multimeter\n\n**Step 2:** Test the sensor independently by printing readings to Serial Monitor\n\n**Step 3:** Test motor actuation with a simple fixed PWM signal\n\n**Step 4:** Integrate the full control algorithm only after individual components work\n\nThis approach simplifies debugging and builds confidence in each subsystem before integration."}], "key_points": ["All components share common ground", "Use motor driver - never drive motor directly from pin", "Consistent wire colors and short signal paths", "Verify each subsystem before integration", "Decoupling capacitors reduce noise"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'bb-lesson-t-circuits';

-- bb-lesson-t-motors: Motors and Motor Controllers
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Motor Fundamentals", "content": "The Ball and Beam system relies on a motor to adjust the angle of the beam in response to the ball''s position. Understanding how motors work and how to control them safely is essential for building a stable and reliable control system.\n\nAt a basic level, a motor converts electrical energy into mechanical motion. In this project, the motor''s job is to rotate a shaft that tilts the beam."}, {"title": "Motor Types", "content": "Depending on the design, the motor may be:\n\n**DC Motor:**\n- Spins continuously when voltage is applied\n- Requires external circuitry to control speed and direction\n- Speed controlled via PWM duty cycle\n\n**Servo Motor:**\n- Contains internal control electronics\n- Moves to a commanded position based on PWM signal\n- Simplifies implementation (no separate feedback loop needed)\n\n**Stepper Motor:**\n- Moves in discrete angular steps\n- Used when precise positioning is required\n- Driver generates required coil switching sequences"}, {"title": "Why Motor Drivers Are Required", "content": "**Critical:** Microcontrollers cannot power motors directly!\n\nMotors require significantly more current than a microcontroller pin can provide. Attempting to drive a motor directly from a pin can permanently damage the board.\n\n**Motor Driver Function:**\n- Acts as interface between low-power logic signals and higher-power motor supply\n- Microcontroller sends control signals to driver\n- Driver handles higher current switching to power motor safely"}, {"title": "Control Methods", "content": "**H-Bridge (for DC motors):**\n- Allows both speed and direction control\n- Speed controlled using PWM duty cycle\n- Direction controlled by toggling logic inputs\n\n```cpp\n// Speed control via PWM\nanalogWrite(MOTOR_PWM_PIN, speed);  // 0-255\n\n// Direction control\ndigitalWrite(DIR_PIN_A, HIGH);\ndigitalWrite(DIR_PIN_B, LOW);  // Forward\n```\n\n**Servo Control:**\n- Single PWM control line\n- Pulse width determines angular position\n- Internal feedback ensures position accuracy\n\n```cpp\n#include <Servo.h>\n\nServo beamServo;\n\nvoid setup() {\n    beamServo.attach(SERVO_PIN);\n}\n\nvoid setBeamAngle(int angle) {\n    beamServo.write(angle);  // 0-180 degrees\n}\n```"}, {"title": "Power Management", "content": "Motors can draw large currents, especially during startup or stall conditions.\n\n**Best Practices:**\n- Use separate power supply for motor\n- Connect all grounds together (common reference)\n- Include flyback diodes for inductive spike protection\n- Test motor behavior independently before implementing feedback control\n\n**Before Full Integration:**\n1. Start with fixed PWM signals or fixed position commands\n2. Observe how the beam responds\n3. Identify mechanical limits, dead zones, and nonlinearities\n4. Use this understanding when tuning the control algorithm"}], "key_points": ["Never drive motor directly from microcontroller pin", "Use motor driver for current handling", "Servo simplifies control with internal feedback", "Separate power supply for motor", "Test motor independently before PID integration"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'bb-lesson-t-motors';

-- bb-lesson-t-sensing: Distance Sensing
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "The Role of Position Sensing", "content": "Accurate position measurement is the foundation of the Ball and Beam control system. The motor adjusts the beam angle, but the system can only stabilize the ball if it knows where the ball is at all times.\n\nDistance sensing provides the feedback signal that makes closed-loop control possible. The sensor measures the ball''s position along the length of the beam and converts that physical position into an electrical signal the microcontroller can process."}, {"title": "Sensor Types", "content": "**Ultrasonic Sensor (e.g., HC-SR04):**\n- Emits short pulse of sound\n- Measures time for echo to return\n- Distance calculated from time-of-flight\n- Uses trigger pin and echo pin\n\n```cpp\n// Ultrasonic distance measurement\ndigitalWrite(TRIG_PIN, HIGH);\ndelayMicroseconds(10);\ndigitalWrite(TRIG_PIN, LOW);\n\nlong duration = pulseIn(ECHO_PIN, HIGH);\nfloat distance = duration * 0.034 / 2;  // cm\n```\n\n**Infrared (IR) Distance Sensor:**\n- Emits infrared light\n- Measures intensity or angle of reflected signal\n- Provides analog voltage output\n- Read using `analogRead()`\n\n**Linear Potentiometer:**\n- Direct position measurement\n- Analog voltage proportional to position\n- Simple and reliable"}, {"title": "Measurement Challenges", "content": "Raw measurements are rarely perfect. Sensor readings may contain:\n- **Noise** - Small random fluctuations\n- **Outliers** - Occasional incorrect readings\n- **Electrical interference** - From motor switching\n- **Mechanical vibrations** - From beam movement\n\nFor this reason, filtering techniques (moving averages, exponential smoothing) are often applied to stabilize the signal before it is used in the control algorithm."}, {"title": "Calibration", "content": "The raw sensor output must be mapped to actual physical distances along the beam.\n\n**Calibration Process:**\n1. Place the ball at known positions\n2. Record sensor readings at each position\n3. Generate a conversion equation or lookup table\n\n```cpp\n// Example: Linear calibration\nfloat calibratePosition(int rawValue) {\n    // Map raw sensor value (0-1023) to beam position (0-30 cm)\n    return map(rawValue, RAW_MIN, RAW_MAX, 0, 30);\n}\n```\n\n**Critical:** Without calibration, the control system may respond incorrectly because it is acting on inaccurate position estimates."}, {"title": "Sampling Rate", "content": "The sensor must be read at consistent intervals within the main control loop.\n\n- **Too slow:** System becomes sluggish and unstable\n- **Too fast without filtering:** Noise dominates the signal\n\nA balanced, consistent update rate ensures accurate and stable feedback.\n\n**Remember:** In a closed-loop control system, the sensor is just as important as the motor. A powerful actuator cannot compensate for poor measurements."}], "key_points": ["Position sensing enables closed-loop control", "Ultrasonic uses time-of-flight measurement", "Raw readings contain noise - filtering required", "Calibration maps raw values to physical distance", "Consistent sampling rate is critical"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'bb-lesson-t-sensing';

-- bb-lesson-t-filtering: Filtering Techniques
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Why Filtering is Essential", "content": "Filtering is a fundamental requirement in real-world control systems because sensors do not operate under ideal conditions. They introduce noise, measurement jitter, dropouts, and occasional spikes.\n\nIn the Ball and Beam system, the HC-SR04 ultrasonic sensor is particularly susceptible to these issues. Its readings can fluctuate due to:\n- Surface reflections\n- Beam angle variation\n- Vibration\n- Electrical noise from the motor\n\n**Critical Impact on PID:**\nThe derivative term of a PID controller is especially sensitive to noise because it estimates how fast the ball is moving based on changes in position. Even small measurement spikes can produce large derivative outputs, amplifying noise and causing aggressive, unstable motor corrections."}, {"title": "Exponential Moving Average (EMA)", "content": "One of the most practical filtering techniques for embedded systems is the Exponential Moving Average (EMA) filter. It is a first-order low-pass, infinite impulse response (IIR) filter.\n\n**The EMA Equation:**\n```\ny_k = alpha * x_k + (1 - alpha) * y_{k-1}\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `x_k` = new measurement\n- `y_k` = filtered output\n- `y_{k-1}` = previous filtered output\n- `alpha` = smoothing constant (0 to 1)\n\n**Effect of Alpha:**\n- **Small alpha (e.g., 0.1):** Heavy smoothing, slower response, less noise\n- **Large alpha (e.g., 0.9):** Quick response, less smoothing, more noise\n\n**Implementation:**\n```cpp\nfloat alpha = 0.2;\nfloat filteredPosition = 0;\n\nfloat applyEMAFilter(float newReading) {\n    filteredPosition = alpha * newReading + (1 - alpha) * filteredPosition;\n    return filteredPosition;\n}\n```\n\n**Advantages:**\n- Only requires storing previous output value\n- Computationally efficient\n- Well-suited for microcontrollers with limited memory"}, {"title": "Kalman Filter (Advanced)", "content": "The Kalman filter is an optimal recursive estimation algorithm used to estimate the state of a linear system from noisy and incomplete measurements.\n\n**Core Idea:**\nCombines a prediction of system behavior with the measured sensor value to produce a more accurate estimate than either would alone.\n\n**Two-Step Process:**\n1. **Prediction:** Estimate next state based on previous behavior\n2. **Correction:** Adjust prediction using new measurement\n\nThe filter automatically balances how much it trusts the model versus the measurement based on predefined uncertainty parameters.\n\n**For this project:** It is acceptable to treat the Kalman filter as a structured estimation tool implemented through a library, rather than focusing on its full mathematical derivation."}, {"title": "Practical Recommendations", "content": "**Starting Point:**\nThe EMA filter is recommended as a starting point due to its simplicity and effectiveness.\n\n**When to Consider Kalman:**\n- Velocity estimation is needed\n- High noise levels are present\n- More sophisticated state estimation required\n\n**Key Takeaway:**\nFiltering is not optional in practical control systems. Clean measurements are essential for stable feedback control. Applying proper filtering techniques ensures that the Ball and Beam system responds smoothly, accurately, and reliably.\n\n**Tuning Tips:**\n1. Start with alpha = 0.2\n2. If response is too slow, increase alpha\n3. If readings are too noisy, decrease alpha\n4. Find balance between responsiveness and stability"}], "key_points": ["Filtering prevents noise from destabilizing control", "EMA is simple and effective for embedded systems", "Small alpha = more smoothing, slower response", "Kalman filter for advanced state estimation", "Filtering is mandatory, not optional"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'bb-lesson-t-filtering';

-- bb-lesson-t-pid: PID Control
UPDATE lessons SET content_json = '{"sections": [{"title": "Understanding PID Control", "content": "This section focuses on building an intuitive understanding of PID control - what each term does, how it affects system behavior, and how to tune the gains manually.\n\nIn the Ball and Beam system, PID control is used to stabilize the ball at a desired position by adjusting the beam angle through the motor. Rather than treating PID as a formula to memorize, the goal is to understand how each component influences motion and stability."}, {"title": "The Feedback Loop", "content": "A PID controller operates within a closed-loop feedback system:\n\n1. **Sensor** measures ball position (process variable)\n2. **Controller** compares measured value to desired position (setpoint)\n3. **Error** is computed (difference between setpoint and measurement)\n4. **PID algorithm** calculates control output\n5. **Actuator** (motor/servo) changes beam angle\n6. **Ball** moves in response\n7. **Loop repeats** continuously\n\n```\nSetpoint --> [Error] --> [PID Controller] --> [Actuator] --> [System]\n              ^                                                 |\n              |                                                 |\n              +--------------- [Sensor] <-----------------------+\n```"}, {"title": "The Three PID Terms", "content": "**Proportional (P) - Reacts to PRESENT error:**\n- If ball is far from center, generates large correction\n- Increasing Kp makes system more aggressive\n- Too much Kp causes oscillation\n\n**Integral (I) - Reacts to PAST error:**\n- Accumulates error over time\n- Eliminates steady-state error (ball slightly off-center)\n- Increasing Ki improves long-term accuracy\n- Too much Ki causes overshoot and slow oscillations\n\n**Derivative (D) - Reacts to RATE OF CHANGE:**\n- Predicts future behavior\n- If ball moving quickly toward setpoint, reduces control effort\n- Increasing Kd improves damping, reduces oscillations\n- Too much Kd amplifies noise\n\n```cpp\nfloat Kp = 1.0, Ki = 0.1, Kd = 0.05;\nfloat previousError = 0;\nfloat integral = 0;\n\nfloat computePID(float setpoint, float measured, float dt) {\n    float error = setpoint - measured;\n    \n    // Proportional\n    float P = Kp * error;\n    \n    // Integral\n    integral += error * dt;\n    float I = Ki * integral;\n    \n    // Derivative\n    float derivative = (error - previousError) / dt;\n    float D = Kd * derivative;\n    \n    previousError = error;\n    \n    return P + I + D;\n}\n```"}, {"title": "Key Terms", "content": "**Process Variable:** The measured quantity being controlled (ball position)\n\n**Setpoint:** The desired value (usually center of beam)\n\n**Error:** Difference between setpoint and measured position\n\n**Actuator:** Device that influences system (motor/servo)\n\n**Control Signal:** Output of PID controller that drives actuator"}, {"title": "Manual Tuning Process", "content": "Manual tuning is an important skill in embedded control systems.\n\n**Step-by-Step Approach:**\n\n1. **Start with Ki = 0 and Kd = 0**\n2. **Increase Kp** until system responds quickly but begins to oscillate slightly\n3. **Introduce Kd** to reduce oscillation and improve damping\n4. **Add small Ki** to eliminate steady-state error\n\n**Tuning Tips:**\n- Change ONE gain at a time\n- Observe system response after each change\n- Record final gain values and performance observations\n- Goal: Balance between responsiveness, stability, and accuracy\n\n**Common Issues:**\n- Oscillation: Kp too high, or Kd too low\n- Slow response: Kp too low\n- Steady-state error: Ki too low\n- Noise amplification: Kd too high, or insufficient filtering"}, {"title": "Why PID Works", "content": "PID controllers are widely used in engineering because they are both simple and powerful. They capture:\n\n- **The Present** through proportional action\n- **The Past** through integration\n- **The Future** through differentiation\n\nBy developing an intuition for how each gain affects motion, you gain the ability to stabilize not only the Ball and Beam system, but also a wide range of real-world control systems involving:\n- Speed\n- Position\n- Temperature\n- Pressure\n- Voltage"}], "key_points": ["P responds to current error", "I eliminates steady-state error", "D reduces oscillation and overshoot", "Tune one gain at a time", "Filter measurements before PID (especially for D term)"], "resources": []}' WHERE id = 'bb-lesson-t-pid';

